      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical) with documented verification test suite; version-controlled input decks stored in institutional repository.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 used throughout. Software quality assurance documented via vendor verification test suite (pass rate 100% on applicable benchmarks). Input decks version-controlled in FDA CDRH GitLab repository with audit trail. Achieves Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions demonstrate correct implementation of linear elastic and contact mechanics formulations.",
      "rationale": "Three benchmark problems executed: (1) cantilever beam deflection, (2) Hertzian contact, (3) cylindrical press-fit. All results within 0.5% of analytical solutions. Code verification requirements at Gradation 2 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change less than 2% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "Four-level mesh refinement study performed on screw shank and rod interface regions. Richardson extrapolation applied; discretization error estimated at 1.1% for stiffness QoI and 1.4% for yield force QoI. GCI < 3% across all QoIs. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence criteria documented; iterative solver residuals below 1e-6 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson nonlinear solver employed with force residual convergence tolerance 1e-6. All 47 load steps across 11 model instances converged without divergence flags. Contact stabilization energy monitored and confirmed negligible (<0.01% of total strain energy). Gradation 2 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments by a second qualified analyst.",
      "rationale": "Independent peer review conducted by a second FDA CDRH analyst not involved in model construction. Boundary condition application, material property assignment, and contact pair definitions verified against documented modeling protocol. No errors identified. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification provided for constitutive model selection; linear elastic with von Mises plasticity appropriate for titanium alloy below ultimate strength.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening constitutive model selected for Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod. Justification: material behavior in the sub-ultimate regime is well-characterized by this model form; literature comparison confirms agreement within 3% for monotonic loading. Geometric nonlinearity (NLGEOM) enabled to capture large-displacement effects at 40 mm. Model form uncertainty estimated at ±4% based on published material model comparisons. Gradation 3 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from coupon testing of same material lot; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and tangent modulus obtained from tensile coupon testing (n=6 per material lot) of Ti-6Al-4V rod and screw stock. CMM measurements performed on all 11 test constructs; as-measured geometry used in corresponding FEA instances. Uncertainty in material inputs quantified via Monte Carlo sampling across measured property distributions; combined material and geometric input uncertainty contributes ±3.2% to stiffness QoI. Note: a planned extension will incorporate formal sensitivity analysis to rank input drivers — this characterization is deferred to a subsequent revision.",
      "uncertaintyNote": "UQ completed for material and geometric variability via Monte Carlo (n=10000 samples). Sensitivity analysis identifying dominant input parameters is planned but not yet executed; dominant drivers therefore remain uncharacterized in this submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test specimens from production-representative stock; traceability to device master record established.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All constructs manufactured from production-representative Ti-6Al-4V stock with full traceability to device master record. Lot homogeneity confirmed by hardness testing. Gradation 3 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple test configurations or loading rates evaluated to characterize sensitivity of QoIs to test condition variation.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 protocol (10 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature, standard fixture geometry). No variation in loading rate or fixture configuration was explored. This limits characterization of QoI sensitivity to test condition parameters and results in achievement of Gradation 2 only, below the required Gradation 3. This gap is noted and accepted given that ASTM F1717 is a standardized protocol with narrow allowable variation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters directly traceable to measured specimen properties; no surrogate material or geometry assumptions.",
      "rationale": "Each of the 11 FEA model instances parameterized using CMM-measured geometry and coupon-derived material properties from the same material lot as the corresponding test specimen. No surrogate assumptions required. Equivalency between simulation inputs and physical test conditions confirmed. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) applied to all three QoIs; E/uval < 1.96 required for acceptance.",
      "rationale": "ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval computed for stiffness (1.31), yield force (1.54), and force at 40 mm (1.78). All values below the 1.96 threshold. Percentage differences: 4.2%, 6.8%, and 7.9% respectively, all within the pre-specified 10% bound. Validation comparison is quantitative and statistically grounded. Gradation 3 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs selected align directly with ASTM F1717 required reporting metrics and with clinically relevant construct performance indicators. Construct stiffness predicts load-sharing behavior; yield force predicts onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm predicts ultimate construct survivability under extreme loading. All three QoIs are required by FDA guidance for pedicle screw submissions. Gradation 3 satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario geometry, loading, and boundary conditions match COU; any differences formally justified.",
      "rationale": "Validation activity uses identical screw geometry, rod diameter, vertebral body block geometry, and loading protocol as specified in the COU. Testing performed at two independent laboratories to confirm reproducibility. The only noted difference from clinical COU is the use of UHMWPE vertebral body surrogates rather than cadaveric bone — this is standard practice per ASTM F1717 and is formally justified by the standardized nature of the protocol. Gradation 3 achieved."
    }
